## Typography & Font Hierarchy

A clear typographic hierarchy helps users scan content, understand structure, and find information quickly. Use consistent type styles across the product.

### Type Scale

Use a **modular scale** (ratio-based sizing) for consistent, harmonious typography. Common scales:
- **1.25 (Major Third)** ‚Äì Subtle, good for dense UIs
- **1.333 (Perfect Fourth)** ‚Äì Balanced, common for applications
- **1.5 (Perfect Fifth)** ‚Äì More dramatic, good for marketing pages

**Example scale (base 16px, ratio 1.25):**
| Level | Size | Use |
|-------|------|-----|
| H1 | 32px (2rem) | Page titles |
| H2 | 26px (1.6rem) | Section headers |
| H3 | 20px (1.25rem) | Subsection headers |
| H4 | 16px (1rem) | Card titles, labels |
| Body | 14-16px | Primary content |
| Caption | 12px (0.75rem) | Helper text, metadata |
| Small | 11px (0.69rem) | Fine print, timestamps |

### Heading Hierarchy Rules

1. **Don't skip levels** ‚Äì Go H1 ‚Üí H2 ‚Üí H3, not H1 ‚Üí H3 (important for accessibility)
2. **One H1 per page** ‚Äì The page title; everything else is H2 or below
3. **Headings describe content** ‚Äì Scannable headings help users find what they need
4. **Consistent styling** ‚Äì Same heading level = same visual treatment everywhere

### Weight & Style

| Weight | Use For |
|--------|---------|
| **Bold (600-700)** | Headings, labels, emphasis, important numbers |
| **Medium (500)** | Subheadings, navigation items, button text |
| **Regular (400)** | Body text, descriptions, form inputs |
| **Light (300)** | Large display text only (not for small sizes) |

### Contrast Through Typography

Create hierarchy without changing size by using:
- **Weight contrast** ‚Äì Bold label + regular value
- **Color contrast** ‚Äì Primary color for key info, muted gray for secondary
- **Case** ‚Äì ALL CAPS for small labels (sparingly), sentence case for content
- **Style** ‚Äì Italic for emphasis or metadata (use sparingly)

### Line Height (Leading)

| Text Type | Line Height |
|-----------|-------------|
| Headings | 1.1 ‚Äì 1.3 (tighter) |
| Body text | 1.4 ‚Äì 1.6 (comfortable reading) |
| Captions | 1.3 ‚Äì 1.4 |

### Common Typography Mistakes

- ‚ùå Too many font sizes (stick to your type scale)
- ‚ùå Body text too small (minimum 14px for UI, 16px preferred)
- ‚ùå Insufficient contrast between heading levels
- ‚ùå Using light weight fonts at small sizes (illegible)
- ‚ùå Line lengths too long (aim for 50-75 characters per line)
- ‚ùå Centered body text (hard to read; left-align instead)

### Typography for Data

| Element | Recommendation |
|---------|----------------|
| **Numbers in tables** | Use tabular/monospace figures for alignment |
| **Large numbers** | Add thousand separators (1,234,567) |
| **Units** | Smaller or lighter weight than the number |
| **Trends (+/-)** | Use color + icon, not just symbols |
| **Empty/null values** | Use "‚Äî" or "N/A", not "0" or blank |

