## Calls to Action (CTAs)

> See also: [Button Hierarchy (Primary / Secondary / Tertiary)](#button-hierarchy-primary--secondary--tertiary) for button styling guidelines.

### Button Labeling

Use clear, action-oriented labels that describe what will happen:

| Bad | Good | Why |
|-----|------|-----|
| "OK" | "Save changes" | Specific about what happens |
| "Submit" | "Create project" | Names the action and object |
| "Click here" | "View documentation" | Descriptive, accessible |
| "Delete" | "Delete project" | Includes the object being deleted |
| "Yes" / "No" | "Delete" / "Keep" | Action-oriented, not just confirmation |

### Labeling Guidelines:
- **Start with a verb** ‚Äì "Save", "Delete", "Export", "Create"
- **Be specific** ‚Äì Include the object when helpful ("Delete project" not just "Delete")
- **Match the trigger** ‚Äì If user clicked "Edit profile", the save button should say "Save profile"
- **Avoid jargon** ‚Äì "Submit" is vague; prefer specific actions

### Disable vs. Hide

| Approach | When to Use |
|----------|-------------|
| **Disable** (grayed out) | Action exists but isn't available yet (e.g., "Save" when form is incomplete) |
| **Hide** | User will never need this action (e.g., admin-only actions for regular users) |
| **Show with explanation** | Action unavailable with a reason (tooltip or helper text explaining why) |

- Disabled buttons (often look grey in color) should have a tooltip explaining why they're disabled
- Don't hide actions and then show them unexpectedly‚Äîusers should understand what's possible

